div.p:
3. For letting in of comfort and joy into the hearts of the children of Promise; Comfort cometh by hearing as well as faith;
Rom. 15 4
                  That you through patience and comfort of the Scriptures might have hope.

The three and twentieth preached upon the parable of Dives and Lazarus, Luke 16. last, I pray thee, father Abraham, send Lazarus to warne my brethren &c. No, saith Abraham, they have Moses and the Prophets, let them heare them, for if they hear not them; they will not be perswaded, though one rose from the dead; He shewed you most excellently what a vain and foolish thing it is to fancy some other way for conversion, and for turning of men to God, then that which God himselfe hath already established; No, saith God, If they will not believe Moses and the Prophets, they will not hear, though one rise from the dead; and he gave clear evidences of it;
truly the first might serve instead of all, it was this: no way that can be thought of will do men good for reformation and conversion, unlesse God set in with it, (mark the foundation upon which he builds his inference) now is it likely and probable God should set in with wayes of mens invention, when they despise the wayes of his own ordination? Suppose one should come from hell all in flames, and tell you what the damned suffer there: is it probable this should do you good, when God tells you the same thing in the Word, and you will not believe him? Its a most convincing argument, men that despise Ministers, and Word,
and Sacraments, and the institutions of God, will never believe a report of a doubtful authority; You have a more sure word of prophecie, 2 Pet. 1.19 whereunto you do well that you take heed, &c. despise it not, lest you provoke God to take away the means you have; and then wo unto you that ever you were borne.
